english:
  title: A Letter to Wang Ruozhou
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow my head and make obeisance twice to you, Elder Brother Wang.

    Four or five days past, Huang-fu Hang came to my lodging to inquire after my illness, and brought word that you, upon hearing of my abandonment of the examinations due to sickness, were moved with compassion and alarm—your concern springing from genuine sincerity. Thus I learned of your magnanimous heart's deep capacity for love and duty.

    Though I have known many companions, none have understood the whole arc of my life's journey as thoroughly as you. Therefore, I wish now to speak plainly with you.

    From youth, I pursued no other arts. The games of strategy, archery, music, horsemanship—all remained foreign to me. I devoted myself solely to reading and the cultivation of letters, seeking thereby to establish myself through merit alone. I scorned to trade upon my family's shadow or rank to advance in the world. Even when my father held power, did I seek position and gain for my own glory? Nay, he often urged me toward office, yet I refused more than once. This was the rashness of youth—my spirit not yet tempered by the world's changes, my heart too straight, my understanding of subtlety too slight.

    Yet my resolve grew ever higher, my integrity ever more steadfast. Thus did my name spread through the world for my writings. Day after day I grew proud, and carelessly offended many. Those who mocked me, who bore me ill will, twisted my words beyond measure. Like a single dog barking at shadows, and a thousand dogs barking at the sound—so was I transformed into a monster in the eyes of the world. Then came my downfall: my every effort crumbled to dust, my fortune scattered like tiles. Lonely and endangered, I found no path to rise again.

    At court, there was none of sufficient standing to rescue me, none upon whose patronage I could climb. My only hope lay in passing the examinations. Yet even this path is now blocked. My decline and peril pierce the heart.

    Some men experience sudden elevation, then decline, yet find redemption in their twilight years. Others never know distinction, yet avoid calamity to life's end. The patterns are many and varied. But why is it that I alone, for even a single day, cannot escape this weight of sorrow? Has the accumulated retribution of my ancestors fallen upon me alone, meant to destroy and prevent my rising? Or is it that my youthful recklessness and folly bred such envy among men that the voice of the crowd has worn me away?

    These are matters beyond knowing. Can you not ease my mind and resolve my doubts?

    There is another strange thing: my contemporaries, observing that I am young and possessed of talent, all speak as one that I might skillfully obtain the degree. Yet this praise, however unanimous, is not what I wish to hear. So shallow is the world's judgment, so reckless its opinions!

    I am not one who pursues fame. Yet when men praise another without regard for truth, is it not better not to be praised at all? If any should venture to speak of me, I ask only this: do not call them a judge of letters.
  footnotes:
    - This is a letter of self-examination written by Lim Chun to his friend and patron Wang Ruozhou, likely composed during a period of political setback when Lim's own examination prospects had been thwarted by illness.
    - The reference to 'a single dog barking at shadows, and a thousand dogs barking at the sound' is a classical idiom suggesting how rumor and misrepresentation can spread and distort one's reputation.
    - The 'examinations' (과거) refer to the civil service examination system, the primary means of advancement in the bureaucracy of medieval East Asia.
